<HEADLINE>
<P>
CSUN OPPONENT PULLS PLUG ON BID TO BROADCAST GAME; 
</P>
<P>
COLLEGE FOOTBALL: CAL POLY SLO OFFICIALS FEAR THAT ALLOWING KADY TO TELEVISE 
DIVISION II PLAYOFF WOULD CUT ATTENDANCE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE HISERMAN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Television station KADY's plans to broadcast Saturday's Division II football 
playoff game between Cal State Northridge and Cal Poly San Luis Obispo were 
scuttled Tuesday by athletic officials from the host school. 
</P>
<P>
San Luis Obispo administrators denied the station permission to broadcast the 1 
p.m. game, saying they feared television coverage might adversely affect 
attendance. KADY had planned to televise the game on a delay basis beginning at 
11 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
The decision, San Luis Obispo officials say, came down to a matter of money. 
</P>
<P>
"We've gotta come up with some big bucks," said Ken Walker, San Luis Obispo's 
athletic director. "We submitted a bid based on a gate and we had to guarantee 
the NCAA a healthy fraction of it. We need to have as many people here as 
possible." 
</P>
<P>
Walker said school officials might change their minds if advance ticket sales 
are brisk, but KADY sports director Clay Morgan said the station no longer is 
interested in televising the game. 
</P>
<P>
"We won't be doing it. We just can't," Morgan said. "If they called us back 
later this week, we'd have to say no. There's just too many logistics 
problems." 
</P>
<P>
Morgan said the station's broadcast of a Nov. 3 regular-season game between the 
same teams drew a very good response. 
</P>
<P>
"We've had a ton of calls, people asking if we were going to do this week's 
game," Morgan said. "I was a little surprised (Cal Poly San Luis Obispo) said 
no. But I understand." 
</P>
<P>
In the teams' earlier meeting, San Luis Obispo (9-1) defeated Northridge (7-3), 
6-3, before a capacity crowd of more than 7,000 at North Campus Stadium. The 
victory earned the Mustangs a share of the WFC championship with CSUN. 
</P>
<P>
Northridge is making its first Division II playoff appearance. 
</P>
<P>
Saturday's game will be broadcast live on radio by KGIL 1260 and KJDJ 1030, 
beginning at 12:45 p.m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA111490-0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 307491 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 14, 1990, Wednesday, Valley Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 15; Column 6 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
475 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
STATWATCH: RESEDA DEFENSE GETS HELP FROM MANY QUARTERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Reseda High, moved from the City Section 3-A Division into the 4-A North Valley 
League this year, is playing for the league title Friday. To no one's surprise, 
the Regents (5-3, 3-3 in league play) have done it with defense. 
</P>
<P>
However, finding a particular standout is tough. The Regents have allowed 
averages of 191.5 yards and 10.1 points a game, but just about everybody has 
been in on the act. 
</P>
<P>
For instance, what do Johnan Reece, Maurice Stepter, Henry McAlpine, Jon Van 
Duinwyk, Edgar Fernandez, Larry Trammel and Tim Schaeffer have in common? 
</P>
<P>
All are tied for the team lead in interceptions . . . with one. 
</P>
<P>
Defense: The El Camino Real defense is even stingier than Reseda's, allowing an 
average of 171.3 yards a game. Eight different Conquistadores have recorded 
interceptions, but only Ryan Marine (two) has more than one. . . . Thousand 
Oaks defensive tackle Mike Ciandella has 12 sacks, five short of the school 
record set last season by Nick Ochoa. 
</P>
<P>
Rushing: Shawn Hardy was among those watching from the Glendale sideline as 
Pathon Rucker broke Hardy's single-season rushing record of 1,715 yards set 11 
years ago. Rucker, a junior, rushed for 209 yards to bring his season total to 
1,767. In addition, he leads all players in the state in scoring (192 points) 
and touchdowns (30). 
</P>
<P>
With his 136 yards Friday, Kennedy tailback Ontiwaun Carter topped the 
1,000-yard mark for the third consecutive season. As a sophomore, Carter rushed 
for 1,190 yards and as a junior, he gained 1,563. He has 1,045 this season. 
</P>
<P>
Westlake's Reuben Allen was limited to a season-low 37 yards Friday, but he 
still set a school record for rushing yards in a season with 1,215, breaking 
Jamin McNeil's 1985 record of 1,204. 
</P>
<P>
Harvard's Kent Dahn scored three touchdowns Saturday to set a single-season 
school mark of 19. 
</P>
<P>
Offense: Ryan Connors has passed for 2,085 yards this season, becoming the 
fifth Hart quarterback in a row to break 2,000. Rob Westervelt passed for 2,064 
yards last season and Tom Bonds, Jim Bonds and Darren Renfro all broke the 
2,000-yard mark. 
</P>
<P>
Five Marmonte League quarterbacks have thrown for more than 1,000 yards, and 
Thousand Oaks' Scott Peterson (966 yards) likely will become the sixth. . . . 
Peterson (15 touchdowns on 59 completions) averages one touchdown every 3.9 
completions. 
</P>
<P>
Sixteen Simi Valley players have caught at least one pass. 
</P>
<P>
