<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: MAN PLEADS NOT GUILTY IN TICKET-FIXING CASE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An employee of the company that processes parking tickets for the city of Los 
Angeles pleaded not guilty Tuesday in Los Angeles Municipal Court to charges of 
attempting to fix parking citations. 
</P>
<P>
Alex Ellis, 32, a customer service representative for Lockheed Information 
Management Services Co., was charged with grand theft, commercial bribery and 
unlawful access to a computer, according to the Los Angeles district attorney's 
office. 
</P>
<P>
He allegedly offered to clear the record of a parking violator with unpaid 
tickets totaling over $1,000; the parking violator then contacted Los Angeles 
police, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
City Parking Administrator Robert Yates said he was not aware of any previous 
allegations against employees of Lockheed, which has held the city contract to 
collect unpaid citations since 1985. City officials have been considering 
renewal of Lockheed's contract, which expired last month. 
</P>
