<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE: VETERAN RETAILER LEN WILLIAMS TAKES PIC 'N' SAVE REINS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JANE APPLEGATE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Pledging to return a bargain-basement flavor to Pic 'N' Save discount stores, 
veteran retailing executive Len Williams on Tuesday assumed the post of 
president and chief executive officer of the Dominguez-based retailer. 
</P>
<P>
His selection Monday ended months of pressure by dissident shareholders to 
replace Lewis B. Merrifield III, who at one time was chairman, president and 
chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
Arthur Frankel, who replaced Merrifield as chairman for four months, resigned 
last week. He was succeeded by Peter S. Willmott, former chairman, president 
and chief executive of Carson, Pirie Scott &amp; Co. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm a hard-core merchant," Williams said. "In a bargain-oriented store, 
impulse creates business, and mass creates impulse." 
</P>
<P>
Williams, former president of Caldor, a division of Associated Dry Goods, and 
former chief executive of Gold Circle, a division of Federated Stores, was 
elected unanimously, according to board member David Batchelder, who heads the 
La Jolla investment group that pushed for Merrifield's ouster. 
</P>
<P>
Williams, 53, reported for work at 7:30 a.m. Tuesday and immediately launched 
plans to woo back shoppers who considered the messy, jumbled stores a 
bargain-hunter's paradise. Under Merrifield's guidance, management had 
organized the merchandise and tidied up the stores, which critics and some 
shareholders said hurt sales. 
</P>
<P>
"I want to make the merchandise accessible and the stores really full," said 
Williams. He said the stores reported very strong Halloween sales and predicts 
that business will pick up as shoppers try to stretch their holiday dollars. 
</P>
<P>
Williams, who will be moving to Southern California from Westport, Conn., said 
he will be earning less than the $975,000 that Merrifield received. 
</P>
<P>
"I'll be at a more market-related, realistic salary," he said. JANE APPLEGATE 
</P>
</TEXT>
