<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: NEWPORT BEACH; 
</P>
<P>
2 SLIGHTLY INJURED IN BALBOA BAY CLUB FIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MATT LAIT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two people suffered minor injuries Tuesday night during a fire that caused 
extensive damage to an apartment at the exclusive Balboa Bay Club, fire 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
A 32-year-old maintenance worker, identified as Leo Pilapil, was taken to Hoag 
Hospital in Newport Beach for treatment of minor smoke inhalation. 
</P>
<P>
John T. Schuler, 76, who lives in the apartment complex at 1221 W. Coast 
Highway, suffered a cut to his right hand and was treated at the scene by 
paramedics. 
</P>
<P>
More than 30 firefighters battled the blaze, which started shortly before 6:30 
p.m. in the kitchen area of Unit 130, Newport Beach Fire Capt. Randy Scheerer 
said. The fire was contained in about 10 minutes, he said. 
</P>
<P>
The resident of the unit, Herlane Levin, was not inside the apartment when the 
fire broke out, Scheerer said. 
</P>
<P>
The cause of the second-alarm fire was under investigation, said Scheerer, who 
added that a damage estimate had not yet been determined. 
</P>
<P>
About 20 units of the complex were evacuated for several hours as firefighters 
mopped up the area and the smoke dissipated. 
</P>
<P>
During the blaze, firefighter Terry Lewis rescued a small white cat named Baby, 
which belongs to Schuler's 77-year-old wife, Eileen. 
</P>
<P>
"He saved my Baby, I can't believe it," Eileen Schuler said. "I was scared to 
death that Baby was in there. It was awful." 
</P>
<P>
John Schuler said his wife tried to go back into the apartment after she 
realized that her cat was still in the unit, which was directly above the 
apartment that was on fire. 
</P>
<P>
"She couldn't get back in because there was too much smoke," he said. 
</P>
<P>
After Lewis saved the cat and handed her back to Eileen Schuler, the relieved 
owner kissed the firefighter. MATT LAIT 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Newport Beach firefighter Terry Lewis rescues a cat from the burning 
Balboa Bay Club, then, top left, collects heartfelt thanks from Eileen Schuler 
for saving her "Baby." Two people suffered minor injuries during the fire on 
Tuesday night. GLENN KOENIG / Los Angeles Times; Photo, Newport Beach 
firefighter Terry Lewis won a kiss and Eileen Schuler's undying thanks for 
rescuing her cat, "Baby," from a fire at the Balboa Bay Club that slightly 
injured two people. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
