<HEADLINE>
<P>
FOG SHROUDS ORANGE COUNTY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JAMES M. GOMEZ, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A thick blanket of fog covered most of Orange County's coastal communities 
early this morning, prompting partial closure of John Wayne Airport and 
snarling rush-hour traffic along the San Diego Freeway, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
"Visibility here is zero," Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Joe Davies 
said at 8:30 a.m. from the John Wayne Airport tower. 
</P>
<P>
Davies said all early morning commercial flights, which normally begin at 7 
a.m., were either canceled or delayed. Flights resumed about 9 a.m., but the 
changes in flight schedules forced air commuters to make last-minute 
adjustments to their plans. 
</P>
<P>
"We sat in the plane for about an hour, then were told to wait," said Greg 
Paydock, one of dozens of businessmen scrambling to banks of phone booths. 
"That was frustrating." 
</P>
<P>
Other passengers sat in the airport coffee shops and bars or browsed in the 
gift shops to pass the time. Some even caught a quick nap. 
</P>
<P>
"You can hang him from a meat hook, and he'll fall asleep," said Irvine 
businessman Pat Diamond about his partner, Phil McCarty, as the latter slouched 
in a chair, lost in sleep. 
</P>
<P>
Rick Dittman, a meteorologist for WeatherData, based in Wichita, Kan, said the 
fog caused problems in many parts of the state. 
</P>
<P>
"The fog is pretty much widespread up and down the coast," he said, adding that 
the fog was created by a storm front in the Gulf of Alaska. 
</P>
<P>
Law-enforcement authorities reported numerous rush-hour traffic collisions as 
motorists tried to get to work in visibility as low as 25 feet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Travelers delayed by fog fill phone booths at John Wayne Airport as they 
attempt to revise plans. KEN HIVELY / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
