<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION; 
</P>
<P>
PANEL HELD BACK AIDS FINDING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A federal panel waited five months before announcing its finding that steroids 
can halve the death rate from the pneumonia that is the leading killer of 
people with AIDS, it was reported today. 
</P>
<P>
The panel withheld the announcement until Oct. 10 because members could not 
agree on how to word their statement, the New York Times said. 
</P>
<P>
Part of the reason they could not agree, said panel Vice Chairman Dr. Paul 
Meier, was that the findings had not yet been accepted at a prestigious medical 
journal, and they feared that an early announcement would jeopardize 
publication. 
</P>
<P>
Many medical journals have a policy of not publishing studies that have been 
reported in the popular press. The journals say the policy is aimed at ensuring 
that studies are subjected to scrutiny by disinterested scientists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
